The Revival of the Great Leader
London — The Battle of Waterloo has long since passed, and Napoleon's catastrophic defeat in that battle severely damaged France's self-respect, to the extent that General de Gaulle omitted any mention of the battle when writing the history of the French military.
Despite this, if you admit that "greatness" is a certain personal quality, then both Napoleon and de Gaulle could be called among the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a "great leader" at all.
In Marx's view, the class struggle in France created the environment in which a "strange mediocrity" like Napoleon could become a hero.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not particularly outstanding as a general, and his victories should be attributed to the courage and devotion of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
Whether or not Napoleon was great, we must determine whether "greatness" can be used to describe any leader.
If the answer is affirmative, then which individuals can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believes that great leaders must meet two particularly important criteria.
First, can this leader recognize the historical trend?
Otto von Bismarck did, as did his German contemporary Konrad Adenauer; borrowing Bismarck's unforgettable phrase, both heard "the rustling of God's cloak."
Second, did this leader make important decisions?
Of course, if a leader is forced to make decisions, they cannot be blamed for it nor credited for it.
Therefore, the key lies in whether the leader had the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the correct decisions on behalf of the nation.
De Gaulle therefore should rightfully be on any list of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he brought France out of the postwar decline.
After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country, suppressed two failed coups, ended the Algerian War, and drafted the Constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle provided the French with a new worldview and established their position in the postwar international order.
In fact, the ultimate impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in shaping their respective national worldviews was somewhat excessive.
Their successors continued to view the world—and the role their own country played—in ways that constrained rational inquiry and distorted decision-making for years to come.
As a result, the leaders of both countries were never able to achieve accomplishments that could match those of the two great leaders.
But there was another British prime minister who could match them: Margaret Thatcher, a highly controversial figure who had as many admirers as detractors.
Even her resignation 25 years earlier stemmed from resistance activities within her own cabinet and party.
But one does not need to please everyone to be a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics cannot deny her influence.
In addition to being the first female prime minister of the United Kingdom and arguably one of the earliest female prime ministers in other countries, Thatcher helped reverse Britain's economic decline.
Not only that, her offensive against overly powerful unions enhanced the nation's manageability at a time when it seemed on the verge of chaos and disorder.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be considered a candidate for the title of "great leader."
Similarly, although far from flawless, Deng Xiaoping also has the right to be considered a candidate for the title of "great leader."
In addition to assisting Mao in wrongdoing, Deng played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen massacre.
But Deng also revitalized the market, leading China onto an unprecedented path of development and prosperity that ultimately enabled hundreds of millions of Chinese people to escape poverty.
Many people consider Lee Kuan Yew, the founder and long-serving prime minister of Singapore, to be very great, although he may have hoped to showcase his talents on a larger stage.
In fact, the size of a country does not seem to affect a person's ability to become a great leader.
I said nothing derogatory about the fact that a small country like Luxembourg is unlikely to produce great leaders, especially since the political climate in the country is generally not highly contentious.
The United States is vast enough to serve as a birthplace of great leaders.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry S. Truman and Dwight D. Eisenhower — although not intellectual giants — demonstrated exceptional judgment in establishing the postwar international order that sustained world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possessed exceptional talent — namely, the ability to inspire and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy was a leader who excelled in multiple areas.
He accomplished a great task: defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His ability to inspire was unparalleled; in fact, his assassination after his death reinforced the tradition he left behind.
In South Africa, no one has yet been considered a great figure after Nelson Mandela's death, as Mandela embodied courage, authority, and graceful magnanimity.
In fact, he was the most charismatic and fascinating leader I have ever met; the other two — former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former U.S. Secretary of State Colin Powell — were either African or African American.
So what about today?
The only one qualified to claim greatness is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at the beginning but made few mistakes when it came to important decisions.
Kohl formulated generous terms for German unification; Merkel opposed Putin during his invasion of Ukraine and adopted a tolerant stance toward the immigration crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy are wrong.
Political leaders — the exercisers of political power — can change the situation for better or worse.
Merkel is the most obvious example today, as she pointed the way for Europe to deal with its difficult survival crisis.
